City Bike Share¶

Introduction¶

Aim: The aim of this analysis is to provide insight on the data and to suggest approaches to optimize bike placement and reallocation schedule for the operator by considering usage patterns during the day and week, weather and ride-distances.

Input data:

  • station.csv - Contains data that represents a station where users can pickup or return bikes.

  • status.csv - data about the number of bikes and docks available for given station and minute.

  • trips.csv - Data about individual bike trips

  • weather.csv - Data about the weather on a specific day for certain zip codes

Assumptions:

  • when choosing to take a trip, passengers would base their decision to cycle on the weather that day i.e. the start_date of the trip
  • in Weather csv, 'T' in precipitation Inches denotes trace percipitation and can be represented as 0
  • In Weather.csv event field, a null value indicates no event.
  • Commuter volume drops on public holidays.

def check_null_values(df):
    ''' Missing values'''
    null_df = pd.DataFrame({'columns': df.columns, 
                            'percent_null': df.isnull().sum() * 100 / len(df), 
                           'percent_zero': df.isin([0]).sum() * 100 / len(df)
                           } )
    return null_df


def count_unique_values(df, categorical_features):
    ''' Cardinality of the categorical variables'''

    cat_df = df[categorical_features]
    val_df = pd.DataFrame({'columns': cat_df.columns, 
                       'cardinality': cat_df.nunique() } )
    return val_df

Volume of trips drops at the weekend. There is also a different distribution of trips over start hour for weekdays vs weekends so it is worthwhile looking at these classes seperately in analysis.

These plots support the hypothesis that the bulk of the patrons are using the service for commuting purposes, with increased patronage during the week and at peak commuting hours for the typical 9-5 job.

The distributions of weekday vs weekend and subscriber vs customer look similar which is reasonable given the class distribution seen earlier.

Summary of Findings¶

  • San Francisco has the highest number of docks and stations, and also the highest number of trips per dock
  • The majority of trips start and finish in a different city. Of the trips that are intercity, Palo Alto and Mountain View are the most common.
  • The majority of trips start and finish in a different station.
  • There are more people with a Subscriber subscription type that customer
  • Weekends and Weekdays are have seperate characteristics.
  • More Subscribers use the service during the week, more customers use the service at weekends.
  • The number of trips is higher on midweek days vs weekend days.
  • On weekdays the number of trips is highest during peak commuting hours
  • On weekends the number of trips is highest in the afternoon approx. 3pm
  • Public holidays show a decrease in number of trips during that day
  • 95% of the trips last less than 30 minutes. 90% of trips last less than 20 minutes. On average, trips taken at the weekend last longer than trips taken during the week. Customer trips tended to last longer than subscriber trips.
  • 99% of trips are under 3.5 km. The average ride distance is 1.33km
  • The stations from which the highest number of trips start are 70, 69, 50, 60, 55.

  • The stations at which the highest number of trips end are 70, 69, 50, 60, 61.

  • Adverse weather conditions such as rain, fog, lower temperatures have a negative relationship with number of trips taken

Conclusion and Suggested Approaches¶

I would suggest having different reallocation schedules for weekdays vs weekends due to the different patterns observed.

Another important note is the different routine for commuting vs leisure. A commuter is likely to repeat their trip in the opposite direction at the end of the day e.g. 70 -> 55 in the morning and 55 -> 70 in the evening. This may not be true for a leisure trip.

One approach would be to take the results of dataset analysis to optimize bike placement and reallocation schedule. Bikes could be moved to the most popular stations away from stations which are not being utilised. Reallocation schedule would be dependant on the weekday vs weekend usage patterns. The mean number of docks and bikes available could be plotted for every station to develop a strategy for individual stations.

Another approach would be to build a Machine Learning model to predict the number of trips that will be taken on a given day, training the model on the historical data and using features such as date, weather, day-of-week, ride-distances. This could be used to optimise reallocation schedule and bike placement. A model to predict number of trips for an individual station could also be used.
